</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Acute lower abdominal and pelvic pain is a frequent complaint of patients in the emergency room. Usually, the condition of these patients is assessed with computed tomography (CT) and ultrasonography (US). However, the need to reduce radiation doses of as much as 20 mSv at CT, especially in younger patients and possibly pregnant patients, and the operator dependence of US have led to an increased use of magnetic resonance (MR) imaging to assess those patients. MR imaging shows high accuracy in these patients and can be used to establish an accurate diagnosis quickly and reliably. A short imaging protocol of about 10 minutes, without the use of an intravenous contrast agent in most cases, allows investigation of these patients. The basic imaging protocol that localizes the diseased anatomic region needs to be complemented by focused anatomic imaging of the diseased area. Although MR imaging might not be the modality of choice for all patients, it may be beneficial for a subset of patients for whom CT is not warranted (pregnant patients or young patients) and US findings are inconclusive. In patients with acute abdominal and pelvic pain, the range of diseases and disorders that can be diagnosed with MR imaging is extremely broad. Therefore, MR imaging should be considered as an excellent imaging modality for the evaluation of these patients.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095518">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095518">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g10a.jpeg" height="1440" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man presenting with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts a large gallbladder (arrows) and a slightly dilated common hepatic duct (arrowhead), but no area of high signal intensity points toward inflammation. Only a central mass with mixed signal intensity attracts the reader’s attention. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) shows a large aortic aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with a diameter of 6.3 cm, and the gallbladder (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) demonstrates the relation of the aneurysm (white <b>*</b>) to its neighboring structures, such as the gallbladder (arrow) and the duodenum (black <b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>) and the gallbladder (arrow). The contrast-enhanced T1-weighted sequence is mandatory in patients with an aneurysm; the sequence delineates the perfused lumen and rules out any contrast agent extravasation. <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates similar findings: the large aortic aneurysm with a wall calcification. The CT image also rules out the possibility of any contrast agent extravasation caused by a rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f10a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g10b.jpeg" height="1037" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man presenting with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts a large gallbladder (arrows) and a slightly dilated common hepatic duct (arrowhead), but no area of high signal intensity points toward inflammation. Only a central mass with mixed signal intensity attracts the reader’s attention. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) shows a large aortic aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with a diameter of 6.3 cm, and the gallbladder (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) demonstrates the relation of the aneurysm (white <b>*</b>) to its neighboring structures, such as the gallbladder (arrow) and the duodenum (black <b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>) and the gallbladder (arrow). The contrast-enhanced T1-weighted sequence is mandatory in patients with an aneurysm; the sequence delineates the perfused lumen and rules out any contrast agent extravasation. <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates similar findings: the large aortic aneurysm with a wall calcification. The CT image also rules out the possibility of any contrast agent extravasation caused by a rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f10b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g10c.jpeg" height="1429" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man presenting with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts a large gallbladder (arrows) and a slightly dilated common hepatic duct (arrowhead), but no area of high signal intensity points toward inflammation. Only a central mass with mixed signal intensity attracts the reader’s attention. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) shows a large aortic aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with a diameter of 6.3 cm, and the gallbladder (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) demonstrates the relation of the aneurysm (white <b>*</b>) to its neighboring structures, such as the gallbladder (arrow) and the duodenum (black <b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>) and the gallbladder (arrow). The contrast-enhanced T1-weighted sequence is mandatory in patients with an aneurysm; the sequence delineates the perfused lumen and rules out any contrast agent extravasation. <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates similar findings: the large aortic aneurysm with a wall calcification. The CT image also rules out the possibility of any contrast agent extravasation caused by a rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f10c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10d-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g10d.jpeg" height="1014" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10d-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man presenting with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts a large gallbladder (arrows) and a slightly dilated common hepatic duct (arrowhead), but no area of high signal intensity points toward inflammation. Only a central mass with mixed signal intensity attracts the reader’s attention. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) shows a large aortic aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with a diameter of 6.3 cm, and the gallbladder (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) demonstrates the relation of the aneurysm (white <b>*</b>) to its neighboring structures, such as the gallbladder (arrow) and the duodenum (black <b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>) and the gallbladder (arrow). The contrast-enhanced T1-weighted sequence is mandatory in patients with an aneurysm; the sequence delineates the perfused lumen and rules out any contrast agent extravasation. <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates similar findings: the large aortic aneurysm with a wall calcification. The CT image also rules out the possibility of any contrast agent extravasation caused by a rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f10d-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10e-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g10e.jpeg" height="1406" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10e-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10e</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man presenting with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts a large gallbladder (arrows) and a slightly dilated common hepatic duct (arrowhead), but no area of high signal intensity points toward inflammation. Only a central mass with mixed signal intensity attracts the reader’s attention. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) shows a large aortic aneurysm (<b>*</b>), with a diameter of 6.3 cm, and the gallbladder (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) demonstrates the relation of the aneurysm (white <b>*</b>) to its neighboring structures, such as the gallbladder (arrow) and the duodenum (black <b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the aneurysm (<b>*</b>) and the gallbladder (arrow). The contrast-enhanced T1-weighted sequence is mandatory in patients with an aneurysm; the sequence delineates the perfused lumen and rules out any contrast agent extravasation. <b>(e)</b> Corresponding axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates similar findings: the large aortic aneurysm with a wall calcification. The CT image also rules out the possibility of any contrast agent extravasation caused by a rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f10e-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g11a.jpeg" height="1376" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the perfused lumen (<b>*</b>), as well as the thrombus (arrows) adhering to the wall of the aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial CT image demonstrates the perfused lumen and the adhering thrombus. In addition, the CT image shows calcifications of the aortic wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f11a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g11b.jpeg" height="1369" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Abdominal aortic aneurysm in a 78-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows the perfused lumen (<b>*</b>), as well as the thrombus (arrows) adhering to the wall of the aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial CT image demonstrates the perfused lumen and the adhering thrombus. In addition, the CT image shows calcifications of the aortic wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f11b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g01a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1669" aria-labelledby="f1a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Complicated perforated diverticulitis with abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150 [repetition time msec/echo time msec/inversion time msec]) demonstrates the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (solid arrow). The abscess (open arrow) is delineated well. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) MR image (2100/101 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) shows thickening of the wall of the colon and narrowing of its lumen (arrowheads). In addition, the abscess contains high-signal-intensity fluid and demonstrates an air-fluid level (arrow) as a sign of perforation. <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an anatomic overview and demonstrates the inflamed bowel (solid arrow) and the abscess (open arrow). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) facilitates the delineation of the bowel wall and lumen (arrowheads) and the formation of an enhancing abscess wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f1a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g01b.jpeg" height="1363" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Complicated perforated diverticulitis with abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150 [repetition time msec/echo time msec/inversion time msec]) demonstrates the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (solid arrow). The abscess (open arrow) is delineated well. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) MR image (2100/101 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) shows thickening of the wall of the colon and narrowing of its lumen (arrowheads). In addition, the abscess contains high-signal-intensity fluid and demonstrates an air-fluid level (arrow) as a sign of perforation. <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an anatomic overview and demonstrates the inflamed bowel (solid arrow) and the abscess (open arrow). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) facilitates the delineation of the bowel wall and lumen (arrowheads) and the formation of an enhancing abscess wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f1b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g01c.jpeg" height="1568" width="1659" aria-labelledby="f1c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Complicated perforated diverticulitis with abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150 [repetition time msec/echo time msec/inversion time msec]) demonstrates the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (solid arrow). The abscess (open arrow) is delineated well. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) MR image (2100/101 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) shows thickening of the wall of the colon and narrowing of its lumen (arrowheads). In addition, the abscess contains high-signal-intensity fluid and demonstrates an air-fluid level (arrow) as a sign of perforation. <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an anatomic overview and demonstrates the inflamed bowel (solid arrow) and the abscess (open arrow). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) facilitates the delineation of the bowel wall and lumen (arrowheads) and the formation of an enhancing abscess wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f1c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1d-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g01d.jpeg" height="1190" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1d-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Complicated perforated diverticulitis with abscess formation in a 58-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150 [repetition time msec/echo time msec/inversion time msec]) demonstrates the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (solid arrow). The abscess (open arrow) is delineated well. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) MR image (2100/101 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]) shows thickening of the wall of the colon and narrowing of its lumen (arrowheads). In addition, the abscess contains high-signal-intensity fluid and demonstrates an air-fluid level (arrow) as a sign of perforation. <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an anatomic overview and demonstrates the inflamed bowel (solid arrow) and the abscess (open arrow). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) facilitates the delineation of the bowel wall and lumen (arrowheads) and the formation of an enhancing abscess wall (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f1d-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1745" aria-labelledby="f2a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Uncomplicated appendicitis in a 34-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (arrowhead) in the right lower quadrant. The retrocecal appendix in this overweight patient was not depicted with US. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the thickened appendix has a diameter of 1.3 cm (arrows), and the surrounding fat is infiltrated (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement that delineates the thickened 4-mm appendiceal wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f2a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g02b.jpeg" height="879" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Uncomplicated appendicitis in a 34-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (arrowhead) in the right lower quadrant. The retrocecal appendix in this overweight patient was not depicted with US. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the thickened appendix has a diameter of 1.3 cm (arrows), and the surrounding fat is infiltrated (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement that delineates the thickened 4-mm appendiceal wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f2b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g02c.jpeg" height="856" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Uncomplicated appendicitis in a 34-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows the high-signal-intensity area of inflammation (arrowhead) in the right lower quadrant. The retrocecal appendix in this overweight patient was not depicted with US. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the thickened appendix has a diameter of 1.3 cm (arrows), and the surrounding fat is infiltrated (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement that delineates the thickened 4-mm appendiceal wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f2c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g03a.jpeg" height="1621" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> A 70-year-old man presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,600/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The tentative diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. The patient’s age made this diagnosis improbable but not impossible. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows pericolic infiltration (arrow) in the area of the ileocecal valve, a finding that increases the probability of appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates wall thickening (arrows) and pericolic fluid in that area, findings that appear to substantiate the tentative diagnosis. <b>(c)</b> However, the coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) shows the elongated sigmoid colon that extends to the right lower quadrant and contains multiple diverticula (arrows), findings that point toward the correct diagnosis of diverticulitis. <b>(d)</b> Optional axial T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates that the inflamed area including the inflamed diverticula (arrowhead) enhances strongly, which proves the perforation and the presence of an abscess (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f3a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g03b.jpeg" height="1104" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> A 70-year-old man presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,600/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The tentative diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. The patient’s age made this diagnosis improbable but not impossible. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows pericolic infiltration (arrow) in the area of the ileocecal valve, a finding that increases the probability of appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates wall thickening (arrows) and pericolic fluid in that area, findings that appear to substantiate the tentative diagnosis. <b>(c)</b> However, the coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) shows the elongated sigmoid colon that extends to the right lower quadrant and contains multiple diverticula (arrows), findings that point toward the correct diagnosis of diverticulitis. <b>(d)</b> Optional axial T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates that the inflamed area including the inflamed diverticula (arrowhead) enhances strongly, which proves the perforation and the presence of an abscess (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f3b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g03c.jpeg" height="1612" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> A 70-year-old man presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,600/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The tentative diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. The patient’s age made this diagnosis improbable but not impossible. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows pericolic infiltration (arrow) in the area of the ileocecal valve, a finding that increases the probability of appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates wall thickening (arrows) and pericolic fluid in that area, findings that appear to substantiate the tentative diagnosis. <b>(c)</b> However, the coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) shows the elongated sigmoid colon that extends to the right lower quadrant and contains multiple diverticula (arrows), findings that point toward the correct diagnosis of diverticulitis. <b>(d)</b> Optional axial T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates that the inflamed area including the inflamed diverticula (arrowhead) enhances strongly, which proves the perforation and the presence of an abscess (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f3c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3d-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g03d.jpeg" height="1116" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3d-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> A 70-year-old man presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,600/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The tentative diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. The patient’s age made this diagnosis improbable but not impossible. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows pericolic infiltration (arrow) in the area of the ileocecal valve, a finding that increases the probability of appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates wall thickening (arrows) and pericolic fluid in that area, findings that appear to substantiate the tentative diagnosis. <b>(c)</b> However, the coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) shows the elongated sigmoid colon that extends to the right lower quadrant and contains multiple diverticula (arrows), findings that point toward the correct diagnosis of diverticulitis. <b>(d)</b> Optional axial T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates that the inflamed area including the inflamed diverticula (arrowhead) enhances strongly, which proves the perforation and the presence of an abscess (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f3d-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g04a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1684" aria-labelledby="f4a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> A 22-year-old woman presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 17,200/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The clinical diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. At US, the appendix could not be depicted. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates high signal intensity suggestive of bowel inflammation (white arrowheads) in the area surrounding the right colic flexure. The caliber difference between the normal ascending colon (<b>*</b>) and the narrowed diseased lumen (black arrowheads) is suggestive of a stenosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) delineates the affected segment of the bowel as a 5-cm-long narrowed colic segment (black arrowhead), which has a wall thickness of 7 mm, and pericolic fluid (white arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement of the thickened bowel wall (arrowhead). Because the patient’s age rendered the diagnoses of diverticulitis and malignancy improbable, the radiologic diagnosis was an acute episode of inflammatory bowel disease (eg, Crohn disease). However, the findings at pathologic examination after surgery showed diverticulitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f4a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g04b.jpeg" height="907" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> A 22-year-old woman presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 17,200/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The clinical diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. At US, the appendix could not be depicted. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates high signal intensity suggestive of bowel inflammation (white arrowheads) in the area surrounding the right colic flexure. The caliber difference between the normal ascending colon (<b>*</b>) and the narrowed diseased lumen (black arrowheads) is suggestive of a stenosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) delineates the affected segment of the bowel as a 5-cm-long narrowed colic segment (black arrowhead), which has a wall thickness of 7 mm, and pericolic fluid (white arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement of the thickened bowel wall (arrowhead). Because the patient’s age rendered the diagnoses of diverticulitis and malignancy improbable, the radiologic diagnosis was an acute episode of inflammatory bowel disease (eg, Crohn disease). However, the findings at pathologic examination after surgery showed diverticulitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f4b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g04c.jpeg" height="940" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> A 22-year-old woman presenting with right-sided abdominal pain and leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 17,200/μL [reference value, &lt;10,000/μL]). The clinical diagnosis of the emergency physician was appendicitis. At US, the appendix could not be depicted. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates high signal intensity suggestive of bowel inflammation (white arrowheads) in the area surrounding the right colic flexure. The caliber difference between the normal ascending colon (<b>*</b>) and the narrowed diseased lumen (black arrowheads) is suggestive of a stenosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) delineates the affected segment of the bowel as a 5-cm-long narrowed colic segment (black arrowhead), which has a wall thickness of 7 mm, and pericolic fluid (white arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) shows strong contrast enhancement of the thickened bowel wall (arrowhead). Because the patient’s age rendered the diagnoses of diverticulitis and malignancy improbable, the radiologic diagnosis was an acute episode of inflammatory bowel disease (eg, Crohn disease). However, the findings at pathologic examination after surgery showed diverticulitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f4c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1512" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Crohn disease in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts the high-signal-intensity area of inflamed bowel (white arrow) and infiltrated visceral fat (arrowhead). In addition, ascites (black arrow) is seen in the pouch of Douglas. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows), thickening of the wall, and pericolic fluid (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows the thickened inflamed bowel wall (arrows) and the in-filtrated fat (arrowheads). Some investigators have suggested that the degree of contrast enhancement is related to the severity of disease (<a href="#b28-0291781" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b28-0291781">28</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f5a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g05b.jpeg" height="1151" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Crohn disease in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts the high-signal-intensity area of inflamed bowel (white arrow) and infiltrated visceral fat (arrowhead). In addition, ascites (black arrow) is seen in the pouch of Douglas. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows), thickening of the wall, and pericolic fluid (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows the thickened inflamed bowel wall (arrows) and the in-filtrated fat (arrowheads). Some investigators have suggested that the degree of contrast enhancement is related to the severity of disease (<a href="#b28-0291781" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b28-0291781">28</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f5b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g05c.jpeg" height="1163" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Crohn disease in a 39-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) depicts the high-signal-intensity area of inflamed bowel (white arrow) and infiltrated visceral fat (arrowhead). In addition, ascites (black arrow) is seen in the pouch of Douglas. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows), thickening of the wall, and pericolic fluid (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows the thickened inflamed bowel wall (arrows) and the in-filtrated fat (arrowheads). Some investigators have suggested that the degree of contrast enhancement is related to the severity of disease (<a href="#b28-0291781" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b28-0291781">28</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f5c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g06a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1763" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> A 28-year-old woman presenting with signs of peritonitis, leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,000/μL [reference value, &lt; 10,000/μL]), and a C-reactive protein level of 72 mg/L (685.57 nmol/L) (reference value, &lt;5 mg/L [&lt;47.62 nmol/L]). <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows dilated fluid-filled small bowel loops (<b>*</b>), as well as wall thickening and segmental narrowing of a long segment of the ileum (arrows) and ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows) can be assigned to the terminal ileum. Note ascites (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an excellent anatomic overview and demonstrates, for example, the empty transverse colon (black arrows), fluid-filled small-bowel loops (<b>*</b>), the inflamed ileum (white arrows), and ascites (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also demonstrates the thickened inflamed ileal wall (arrows). No enlarged lymph nodes were depicted. The findings at pathologic examination of the excised ileum proved the diagnosis of Crohn disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f6a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g06b.jpeg" height="1627" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> A 28-year-old woman presenting with signs of peritonitis, leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,000/μL [reference value, &lt; 10,000/μL]), and a C-reactive protein level of 72 mg/L (685.57 nmol/L) (reference value, &lt;5 mg/L [&lt;47.62 nmol/L]). <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows dilated fluid-filled small bowel loops (<b>*</b>), as well as wall thickening and segmental narrowing of a long segment of the ileum (arrows) and ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows) can be assigned to the terminal ileum. Note ascites (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an excellent anatomic overview and demonstrates, for example, the empty transverse colon (black arrows), fluid-filled small-bowel loops (<b>*</b>), the inflamed ileum (white arrows), and ascites (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also demonstrates the thickened inflamed ileal wall (arrows). No enlarged lymph nodes were depicted. The findings at pathologic examination of the excised ileum proved the diagnosis of Crohn disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f6b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g06c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1493" aria-labelledby="f6c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> A 28-year-old woman presenting with signs of peritonitis, leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,000/μL [reference value, &lt; 10,000/μL]), and a C-reactive protein level of 72 mg/L (685.57 nmol/L) (reference value, &lt;5 mg/L [&lt;47.62 nmol/L]). <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows dilated fluid-filled small bowel loops (<b>*</b>), as well as wall thickening and segmental narrowing of a long segment of the ileum (arrows) and ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows) can be assigned to the terminal ileum. Note ascites (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an excellent anatomic overview and demonstrates, for example, the empty transverse colon (black arrows), fluid-filled small-bowel loops (<b>*</b>), the inflamed ileum (white arrows), and ascites (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also demonstrates the thickened inflamed ileal wall (arrows). No enlarged lymph nodes were depicted. The findings at pathologic examination of the excised ileum proved the diagnosis of Crohn disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f6c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6d-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g06d.jpeg" height="1598" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6d-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> A 28-year-old woman presenting with signs of peritonitis, leukocytosis (white blood cell count, 14,000/μL [reference value, &lt; 10,000/μL]), and a C-reactive protein level of 72 mg/L (685.57 nmol/L) (reference value, &lt;5 mg/L [&lt;47.62 nmol/L]). <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) shows dilated fluid-filled small bowel loops (<b>*</b>), as well as wall thickening and segmental narrowing of a long segment of the ileum (arrows) and ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial half-Fourier RARE MR image (2100/101) demonstrates that the inflamed segment of the bowel (arrows) can be assigned to the terminal ileum. Note ascites (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Optional coronal true FISP MR image (4.3/2.2) provides an excellent anatomic overview and demonstrates, for example, the empty transverse colon (black arrows), fluid-filled small-bowel loops (<b>*</b>), the inflamed ileum (white arrows), and ascites (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Optional axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also demonstrates the thickened inflamed ileal wall (arrows). No enlarged lymph nodes were depicted. The findings at pathologic examination of the excised ileum proved the diagnosis of Crohn disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f6d-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g07a.jpeg" height="1220" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Symptomatic ovarian cyst in a 29-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates strong contrast enhancement of the wall (arrows) of an ovarian cyst, a finding suggestive of high perfusion. <b>(b)</b> ADC map shows that the entire cyst (arrows) demonstrates high signal intensity. <b>(c)</b> On an axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value, 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) the fluid content of the cyst (arrows) is depicted as hypointense and the solid, highly perfused wall is depicted as hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f7a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g07b.jpeg" height="1230" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Symptomatic ovarian cyst in a 29-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates strong contrast enhancement of the wall (arrows) of an ovarian cyst, a finding suggestive of high perfusion. <b>(b)</b> ADC map shows that the entire cyst (arrows) demonstrates high signal intensity. <b>(c)</b> On an axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value, 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) the fluid content of the cyst (arrows) is depicted as hypointense and the solid, highly perfused wall is depicted as hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f7b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g07c.jpeg" height="1202" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Symptomatic ovarian cyst in a 29-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) demonstrates strong contrast enhancement of the wall (arrows) of an ovarian cyst, a finding suggestive of high perfusion. <b>(b)</b> ADC map shows that the entire cyst (arrows) demonstrates high signal intensity. <b>(c)</b> On an axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value, 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) the fluid content of the cyst (arrows) is depicted as hypointense and the solid, highly perfused wall is depicted as hyperintense.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f7c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g08a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1579" aria-labelledby="f8a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Tubo-ovarian abscess in a 26-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> ADC map displays restricted diffusion in central areas of necrosis (white <b>*</b>) as hypointense regions. In addition, septal areas (arrowheads) with less-restricted diffusion exist within the abscess. Free fluid (black <b>*</b>) is depicted as hyperintense. <b>(b)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value, 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows central areas of necrosis (black <b>*</b>) as hyperintense and also shows septal areas (arrowheads) with less-restricted diffusion. The signal of free fluid (white <b>*</b>) is completely canceled.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f8a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g08b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1653" aria-labelledby="f8b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Tubo-ovarian abscess in a 26-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> ADC map displays restricted diffusion in central areas of necrosis (white <b>*</b>) as hypointense regions. In addition, septal areas (arrowheads) with less-restricted diffusion exist within the abscess. Free fluid (black <b>*</b>) is depicted as hyperintense. <b>(b)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> value, 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows central areas of necrosis (black <b>*</b>) as hyperintense and also shows septal areas (arrowheads) with less-restricted diffusion. The signal of free fluid (white <b>*</b>) is completely canceled.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f8b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g09a.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Ischemic bowel in a 52-year-old woman presenting with episodes of abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates increased signal intensity in thickened small bowel loops (arrows) but no exudation, abscess, or ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows thickened bowel wall (arrows), which has slightly diminished contrast enhancement compared with normal segments (arrowheads), findings suggestive of ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent angiographic image demonstrates the occlusion of the celiac trunk as well as the superior and inferior mesenteric arteries (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f9a-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g09b.jpeg" height="1667" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9b-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Ischemic bowel in a 52-year-old woman presenting with episodes of abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates increased signal intensity in thickened small bowel loops (arrows) but no exudation, abscess, or ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows thickened bowel wall (arrows), which has slightly diminished contrast enhancement compared with normal segments (arrowheads), findings suggestive of ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent angiographic image demonstrates the occlusion of the celiac trunk as well as the superior and inferior mesenteric arteries (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f9b-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9c-0291781" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095518/asset/images/g09oc16g09c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1246" aria-labelledby="f9c-0291781" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Ischemic bowel in a 52-year-old woman presenting with episodes of abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal STIR MR image (8100/141/150) demonstrates increased signal intensity in thickened small bowel loops (arrows) but no exudation, abscess, or ascites. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (100/2.5) also shows thickened bowel wall (arrows), which has slightly diminished contrast enhancement compared with normal segments (arrowheads), findings suggestive of ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent angiographic image demonstrates the occlusion of the celiac trunk as well as the superior and inferior mesenteric arteries (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095518&amp;id=f9c-0291781">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291781" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Urban BA, Fishman EK. Renal lymphoma: CT patterns with emphasis on helical CT. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2000;20:197–212.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiographics.20.1.g00ja09197">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10682781/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Renal+lymphoma%3A+CT+patterns+with+emphasis+on+helical+CT&amp;author=BA+Urban&amp;author=EK+Fishman&amp;publication_year=2000&amp;journal=RadioGraphics&amp;pages=197-212&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiographics.20.1.g00ja09197&amp;pmid=10682781">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0291781" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Pereira JM, Sirlin CB, Pinto PS, Jeffrey RB, Stella DL, Casola G. Disproportionate fat stranding: a helpful CT sign in patients with acute abdominal pain. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2004;24:703–715.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.243035084">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15143223/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Disproportionate+fat+stranding%3A+a+helpful+CT+sign+in+patients+with+acute+abdominal+pain&amp;author=JM+Pereira&amp;author=CB+Sirlin&amp;author=PS+Pinto&amp;author=RB+Jeffrey&amp;author=DL+Stella&amp;author=G+Casola&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=RadioGraphics&amp;pages=703-715&amp;doi=10.1148%2Frg.243035084&amp;pmid=15143223">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="b3-0291781" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Miller F, Bree R, Rosen M, et al. <em>ACR Appropriateness Criteria<sup>®</sup> October 2008</em>. American College of Radiology Web site. <a href="http://www.acr.org/">http://www.acr.org/</a>. <span class="named-content" data-type="access-date">Acce